$(
We have not yet defined relations, but here but introduce a few related
notions we will use to develop ordinals.  The class variable ` R ` is no
different from other class variables, but it reminds us that normally it
represents what we will later call a "relation."
$)

  $( Declare new constant symbols. $)
  $c E $. $( Letter E (for epsilon relation) $)
  $c I $.  $( Letter I (for identity relation) $)
  $c Po $.  $( Partial ordering predicate symbol (read: 'partial ordering'). $)
  $c Or $.  $( Strict ordering predicate symbol (read: 'orders'). $)
  $c sup $.  $( Supremum. $)
  $c Fr $. $( Founded predicate symbol (read: 'founded'). $)
  $c We $. $( Well-ordering predicate symbol (read: 'well orders') $)

  $( Extend wff notation to include the general binary relation predicate.
     Note that this is simply three class symbols in a row. $)
  wbr $a wff A R B $.

  $( Extend class notation to include abstraction classes of ordered pairs. $)
  copab $a class { <. x , y >. | ph } $.

  $( Extend class notation to include the epsilon relation. $)
  cep $a class E $.

  $( Extend the definition of a class to include identity relation. $)
  cid $a class I $.

  $( Extend wff notation to include the partial ordering predicate.  Read:
     '` R ` is a partial order on ` A `.' $)
  wpo $a wff R Po A $.

  $( Extend wff notation to include the strict ordering predicate.  Read:
     '` R ` orders ` A `.' $)
  wor $a wff R Or A $.

  $( Extend class notation to include supremum of class ` A `.  Here ` R `
     is ordinarily a relation that strictly orders class ` B `.  For example,
     ` R ` could be "less than" and ` B ` could be the set of real numbers. $)
  csup $a class sup ( A , B , R ) $.

  $( Extend wff notation to include the founded predicate.  Read:  '` R ` is a
     founded relation on ` A `.' $)
  wfr $a wff R Fr A $.

  $( Extend wff notation to include the well-ordering predicate.  Read:  '`R `
     well-orders ` A `.' $)
  wwe $a wff R We A $.

  $( Define a notation for a general binary relation.  Definition 6.18, p. 29,
      of Takeuti and Zaring, generalized to arbitrary classes.  This definition
      is well-defined, although not very meaningful, when classes ` A ` and/or
      ` B ` are proper classes (i.e. are not sets). $)
  df-br $a |- ( A R B <-> <. A , B >. e. R ) $.

